ether such a “youth bulge” increases the potential for conflict or whether it represents a chance to accumulate wealth and push forward social and technological developments. This book introduces the discussion about youth bulge into social anthropology using Tajikistan, a post-Soviet country that experienced civil war in the 1990s, which is in the middle of such a demographic transition. Sophie Roche develops a social anthropological approach to analyze demographic and political dynamics, and suggests a new way of thinking about social change in youth bulge societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAge distribution (Demography)zTajikistan. 0aYouthzTajikistanxSocial conditions. 0aYouthzTajikistan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aSchlee, Günther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238263840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782382638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782382638/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK